questions.question:
Consider a 2-way set associative cache with 256 blocks and uses LRU replacement. Initially the cache is empty. Conflict misses are those misses which occur due to the contention of multiple blocks for the same cache set. Compulsory misses occur due to first time access to the block. The following sequence of access to memory blocks:
{0, 128, 256, 128, 0, 128, 256, 128, 1, 129, 257, 129, 1, 129, 257, 129}
is repeated 10 times. The number of conflict misses is ________.

steps.apply:
Access 0: miss (compulsory), cache={0}
Access 128: miss (compulsory), cache={0,128}
Access 256: miss (compulsory), cache={128,256} (LRU=0, evict 0)
Access 128: HIT, cache={256,128}
Access 0: miss, cache={128,0} (LRU=256, evict 256) -- Is this conflict? 0 was evicted earlier, so yes.
Access 128: HIT, cache={0,128}
Access 256: miss, cache={128,256} (LRU=0, evict 0)
Access 128: HIT, cache={256,128}
First iteration set 0: 3 compulsory + 2 conflict misses.

At start of each repeat, cache for set 0 holds {256,128} (from end of prev iteration).
Access 0: miss (conflict, 0 evicted), cache={128,0}
Access 128: HIT
Access 256: miss (conflict, 256 evicted), cache={0... wait let me recheck.
From {128,256}: Access 0 misses, evict LRU=128, cache={256,0}. Access 128: miss, evict LRU=256, cache={0,128}. Access 256: miss, evict LRU=0, cache={128,256}. Access 128: HIT. Access 0: miss, evict LRU=256... Actually the pattern {0,128,256,128,0,128,256,128} from state {256,128}:
- 0: miss, evict 256, cache={128,0}
- 128: HIT, cache={0,128}
- 256: miss, evict 0, cache={128,256}
- 128: HIT, cache={256,128}
- 0: miss, evict 256, cache={128,0}
- 128: HIT
- 256: miss, evict 0, cache={128,256}
- 128: HIT
Each repetition after first: 4 conflict misses for set 0.
